unique(airline_tweets$airline)

## [5] "US Airways"     "American"
unique(airline_tweets$airline_sentiment)
## [1] "neutral"  "positive" "negative"
table(airline_tweets$airline)
## 
##       American          Delta      Southwest         United     US Airways 
##           2759           2222           2420           3822           2913 
## Virgin America 
##            504
table(airline_tweets$airline_sentiment)
## 
## negative  neutral positive 
##     9178     3099     2363

  1. There are 6 unique values in airline: Virgin America, United, Southwest, Delta, US Airways, and American. And there are 3 unique values in airline_sentiment: neutral, positive, negative.

  2. The table function tells us the counts for each unique value, as shown in the code above.

Problem 3

library(ggplot2)
airline_dist_plot <- ggplot(data = airline_tweets, aes(x=airline))
airline_dist_plot + geom_bar() + coord_cartesian()

airline_dist_plot + geom_bar(aes(fill = airline)) + coord_cartesian()

airline_dist_plot + geom_bar(fill = "blue") + coord_cartesian()

airline_dist_plot + geom_bar(fill = "blue") + coord_cartesian() + ggtitle("Number of Tweets by Airlines")

  1. R labeled the x-axis by the name of the variable we defined in aes, airline, and the categories of the variable. The bar chart has default y-axis label count.

airline_dist_plot + geom_bar(fill = "blue") + coord_cartesian() + ggtitle("Number of Tweets by Airlines") + 
  labs(x = "Airline", y = "Number of Tweets")

  1. United Airlines was the subject of the most tweets, and Virgin America Airline the fewest. American Airlines and US Airway had similar number of tweets, and Delta and Southwest have similar number of tweets as well. And about 500 tweets were about Virgin America.

airline_dist_plot + geom_bar(fill = "blue") + coord_polar() + ggtitle("Number of Tweets by Airlines") + 
  labs(x = "Airline", y = "Number of Tweets")

Changing to coord_polar() instead plots the numbers on a polar coordinate, and the count (or number) is represented by the radius of each fan-shaped graph, and this is a rose diagram.

  1. I prefer the bar chart created in (f). I am more familiar with the bar chart than the latter. Though its easier to discern the differences in a rose diagram, it is easier to estimate the exact number of tweets for each airline and compare magnitudes across different airlines on a bar chart.

Problem 4

airline_sentiment_dist_plot <- ggplot(data = airline_tweets, aes(x=airline_sentiment))
airline_sentiment_dist_plot + geom_bar(aes(fill = airline_sentiment)) + coord_cartesian() + 
  labs(title = "Number of Tweets by Airline Sentiment", x = "Airline Sentiment", y = "Number of Tweets")

  1. Negative sentiments were the most common, around 9000 tweets, and positive were the least common.
